  "prompt": "Who invented the concept of money?",
  "response": "The concept of money did not have a single inventor but evolved over thousands of years to facilitate trade and economic exchange. Early human societies operated on barter systems, where goods and services were directly exchanged. However, barter systems had limitations, such as the \"double coincidence of wants,\" where both parties had to desire what the other offered.\n\nTo overcome these challenges, societies began using objects with intrinsic value as a medium of exchange. The earliest forms of money included commodities like grain, livestock, shells (e.g., cowrie shells), and metals. Around **3000 BCE**, ancient Mesopotamians used standardized weights of silver and barley as a form of currency.\n\nThe first coins are attributed to the ancient Lydians (in modern-day Turkey) around **600 BCE**, which were made from electrum, a natural alloy of gold and silver. This marked a significant step toward modern money. Later, paper money emerged in **China during the Tang Dynasty (7th century CE)** and became widespread during the Song Dynasty (11th century CE).\n\nThe concept of money has continued to evolve, leading to today's complex financial systems, including digital and cryptocurrency. Its invention was a collective, gradual process driven by the need for efficient trade and economic organization.",
